<br>
If you join a group and don’t ask what the looting rules were, you have no right to be upset with the warrior when he claims the Codpiece of Hammering.<br>
<br>
I asked to join a group once and was invited in.  The looting rules were “everything goes to [Frank].”  The reasons that Frank got to loot everything were many and varied, and they have no real bearing on this thread.<br>
<br>
I agreed.  I didn’t particularly like the rules as I was a bit short of cash, but they were the only group willing to take me and I didn’t relish hiking to another zone or trying to solo.<br>
<br>
Later, another player joined and they explained the loot rules, which caused her to get quite upset.  “Not fair” and “lame” were some of the terms used, as I recall.  The group leader patiently asked if they were going to abide by the rules or not, and when the new arrival refused he wished her luck and booted her out of the group.<br>
<br>
That person later started her own group with drips and drabs that later came into the zone and did all right for herself, I guess.<br>
<br>
So what is my point with this story?  That might makes right?  That you sometimes have to live with lousy looting rules?  That you should suck it up and quit whining?<br>
<br>
Well, ‘yes’ to all of the above.  But the primary thing I’m trying to get across is that for a pick-up group, as long as the rules are known at the outset, you have no right to whine when it actually occurs.  You knew the score.<br>
<br>
If, on the other hand, you DON’T know the loot rules until the rare item in question is lying on the ground… then you still don’t have a lot of leeway to complain, because you were too lazy to ask what the rules were.<br>
